Kubernetes CNI & Calico Crash Course

I’m treating CNI as Kubernetes Container Network Interface and Calico as Project Calico.

1. What is CNI?

CNI is not itself a network. It is a standard interface used by container runtimes such as containerd or CRI-O to call networking plugins. The plugin creates the pod interface, assigns an IP address, configures routes and removes those resources when the pod is deleted. Kubernetes requires a compatible CNI plugin to implement pod networking.

Think of it like this:

Kubernetes
    ↓
Kubelet
    ↓
Container Runtime: containerd / CRI-O
    ↓
CNI specification
    ↓
Calico / Cilium / Flannel / AWS VPC CNI
    ↓
Linux networking
CNI lifecycle

When a pod is created:

1. Kubelet asks containerd to create the pod sandbox.
2. Containerd creates the network namespace.
3. Containerd calls the CNI plugin with CNI_COMMAND=ADD.
4. CNI creates the pod interface.
5. IPAM assigns an IP address.
6. Routes and networking rules are installed.
7. The plugin returns the result to containerd.
8. The pod containers start.

When the pod is removed, the runtime calls the plugin with CNI_COMMAND=DEL. Current CNI operations include ADD, DEL, CHECK, GC, and VERSION; parameters such as the container ID, network namespace and interface name are passed through environment variables.

Common Linux locations are:

/etc/cni/net.d/     CNI configuration files
/opt/cni/bin/       CNI plugin binaries

These are common defaults; the container runtime ultimately controls the configured paths.

2. What is Calico?

Calico provides:

Pod networking
IP address management
Kubernetes NetworkPolicy enforcement
Calico-specific security policies
BGP-based routing
VXLAN and IP-in-IP overlays
iptables, nftables and eBPF data planes
Network observability

Calico can act as the complete CNI, IPAM and policy solution, or it can provide only network policy while another plugin—such as AWS VPC CNI—handles pod networking.

The most important Calico components
Component	Purpose
Calico CNI	Connects a pod to the node network
Calico IPAM	Allocates pod IP addresses
Felix	Programs routes and security rules on every node
BIRD	Advertises pod routes using BGP
confd	Builds BIRD configuration from Calico data
kube-controllers	Synchronizes Kubernetes objects with Calico
Typha	Reduces API/datastore load in larger clusters
Tigera Operator	Installs and manages Calico components
Calico API server	Exposes Calico resources through kubectl
calicoctl	Administrative CLI for Calico resources

Felix is the main node agent. It manages interfaces, kernel routes, access-control rules and node networking state. BIRD is needed when Calico uses BGP route distribution; it is not required for every deployment mode.

3. How Calico connects a pod

Calico normally creates a veth pair:

Pod network namespace                   Node network namespace

+-------------------------+             +-----------------------------+
| Pod                     |             | Kubernetes node             |
|                         |             |                             |
| eth0  192.168.10.5      |-------------| caliXXXXXXXX                 |
|        veth end         |  veth pair  | host-side veth              |
+-------------------------+             |                             |
                                        | Linux routing table         |
                                        | Felix security rules        |
                                        +-----------------------------+

Unlike bridge-based implementations, Calico primarily uses Layer 3 routing. The host-side interface usually starts with cali, and Linux routes packets toward the appropriate pod interface.

Inspect it with:

kubectl get pods -A -o wide

ip link show
ip addr show
ip route show

ip link show | grep cali
ip route | grep 192.168
4. Calico networking modes
A. VXLAN overlay
Pod packet
   ↓
Encapsulated inside VXLAN
   ↓
Transferred between node IP addresses
   ↓
Decapsulated on destination node
   ↓
Destination pod

Use VXLAN when the physical network does not know how to route pod IP addresses. It is generally the easiest portable option for cloud, lab and mixed network environments. VXLAN-only Calico networking does not require BGP unless routes must also be advertised to external BGP peers.

B. IP-in-IP overlay

Similar to VXLAN, but the pod packet is placed inside another IP packet. Calico’s IP-in-IP networking normally uses BGP between nodes for route distribution and supports IPv4 rather than IPv6.

C. BGP without encapsulation

Each node advertises routes for its pod addresses:

Node 1: 192.168.1.0/24
Node 2: 192.168.2.0/24
Node 3: 192.168.3.0/24

The resulting data path is efficient because packets are routed directly without overlay headers. However, the underlying network or routers must accept and route the pod CIDRs. Calico supports node-to-node BGP mesh and external BGP peers such as top-of-rack routers.

D. Cross-subnet overlay
Same subnet       → Direct routing
Different subnet  → VXLAN or IP-in-IP encapsulation

This reduces encapsulation while avoiding the need to teach the whole physical network about pod routes.

Simple selection guide
Environment	Practical starting choice
Local Kind/Minikube lab	VXLAN
Unknown physical network	VXLAN
On-prem with BGP-capable routers	BGP, no overlay
Several Layer 2 subnets	VXLAN CrossSubnet
EKS using native VPC pod addresses	AWS VPC CNI + Calico policy
Maximum Linux performance	Consider Calico eBPF
5. Calico IPAM

Calico IPAM assigns IP addresses from IPPool resources. Pools are divided into smaller blocks that are associated with nodes, allowing IP allocation to grow dynamically rather than reserving a fixed large subnet for every node.

Check IP pools:

kubectl get ippools.projectcalico.org

kubectl get ippools.projectcalico.org -o yaml

Using calicoctl:

calicoctl get ippool -o wide
calicoctl ipam show
calicoctl ipam show --show-blocks

A typical pool looks like:

apiVersion: projectcalico.org/v3
kind: IPPool
metadata:
  name: default-ipv4-ippool
spec:
  cidr: 192.168.0.0/16
  blockSize: 26
  natOutgoing: true
  nodeSelector: all()
  vxlanMode: CrossSubnet
  ipipMode: Never

Important fields:

Field	Meaning
cidr	Address range assigned to pods
blockSize	Smaller allocation block handed to a node
natOutgoing	SNAT pod traffic going outside the pool
vxlanMode	Never, Always, or CrossSubnet
ipipMode	Never, Always, or CrossSubnet
nodeSelector	Nodes allowed to use this pool

Do not casually modify a production pool after pods have already received addresses. Pool migration should be planned so existing workloads can be recreated safely.

6. Kubernetes NetworkPolicy vs Calico Policy
Kubernetes NetworkPolicy

Kubernetes NetworkPolicy is:

Namespace-scoped
Applied to pods selected by labels
Additive
Primarily allow-list based
Split into ingress and egress
Enforced only when the CNI supports NetworkPolicy

A pod is open by default. Once an ingress or egress policy selects it, traffic in that direction becomes isolated and only explicitly allowed traffic passes.

Namespace default deny
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: default-deny
  namespace: production
spec:
  podSelector: {}
  policyTypes:
    - Ingress
    - Egress

Apply:

kubectl apply -f default-deny.yaml

This also blocks DNS egress unless DNS is separately allowed.

Allow frontend to backend on port 8080
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-frontend
  namespace: production
spec:
  podSelector:
    matchLabels:
      app: backend

  policyTypes:
    - Ingress

  ingress:
    - from:
        - podSelector:
            matchLabels:
              app: frontend
      ports:
        - protocol: TCP
          port: 8080
Calico NetworkPolicy

Calico extends Kubernetes policies with capabilities such as:

Explicit Allow, Deny, Log and Pass actions
Policy ordering
Global policies
Host endpoint policies
Service-account selectors
Advanced selectors
CIDR and network-set controls

Calico’s namespaced NetworkPolicy applies within a namespace, while GlobalNetworkPolicy can apply across namespaces and to other endpoint types.

Calico explicit deny example
apiVersion: projectcalico.org/v3
kind: GlobalNetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: restrict-sensitive-workloads
spec:
  order: 100
  selector: security == "restricted"
  types:
    - Egress

  egress:
    - action: Deny

Policies with lower numeric order values are evaluated earlier. Design policy ordering carefully; an incorrect global deny can interrupt cluster traffic.

7. Hands-on Kind + Calico lab

The current Calico Open Source documentation identifies the 3.32 release line as latest and provides an operator-based Kind quickstart.

Requirements

Install:

Docker
kind
kubectl
Step 1: Create a Kind cluster without the default CNI

Create config.yaml:

kind: Cluster
apiVersion: kind.x-k8s.io/v1alpha4

nodes:
  - role: control-plane
  - role: worker
  - role: worker

networking:
  disableDefaultCNI: true
  podSubnet: 192.168.0.0/16

Create the cluster:

kind create cluster \
  --name calico-cluster \
  --config config.yaml

Initially, the nodes may show NotReady because no CNI has configured networking yet.

kubectl get nodes -o wide
Step 2: Install Calico
kubectl create -f \
https://raw.githubusercontent.com/projectcalico/calico/v3.32.1/manifests/v1_crd_projectcalico_org.yaml

kubectl create -f \
https://raw.githubusercontent.com/projectcalico/calico/v3.32.1/manifests/tigera-operator.yaml

kubectl create -f \
https://raw.githubusercontent.com/projectcalico/calico/v3.32.1/manifests/custom-resources.yaml

These commands follow the current official quickstart; pin the version rather than blindly installing an unversioned manifest in production.

Monitor installation:

watch kubectl get tigerastatus

Check components:

kubectl get pods -n tigera-operator
kubectl get pods -n calico-system -o wide
kubectl get nodes
Step 3: Create test applications
kubectl create namespace quickstart

kubectl create deployment nginx \
  --namespace quickstart \
  --image nginx

kubectl expose deployment nginx \
  --namespace quickstart \
  --port 80

Start a client:

kubectl run access \
  --namespace quickstart \
  --rm -it \
  --image busybox \
  --labels="app=client" \
  -- /bin/sh

Inside the pod:

wget -qO- http://nginx
nslookup nginx
ip addr
ip route

This follows the official Calico connectivity test pattern.

