9. CNI and Calico troubleshooting workflow

Follow the packet from Kubernetes downward rather than randomly restarting components.

Level 1: Is the pod sandbox failing?
kubectl describe pod <pod-name> -n <namespace>

Look for messages such as:

FailedCreatePodSandBox
networkPlugin cni failed
plugin type="calico" failed
failed to assign an IP address
connection is unauthorized
Level 2: Is the node ready?
kubectl get nodes
kubectl describe node <node-name>

Common condition:

NetworkPluginNotReady
cni plugin not initialized
Level 3: Is Calico running on the node?
kubectl get pods -n calico-system -o wide

kubectl logs -n calico-system \
  <calico-node-pod> \
  -c calico-node

Previous container logs:

kubectl logs -n calico-system \
  <calico-node-pod> \
  -c calico-node \
  --previous

Operator logs:

kubectl logs -n tigera-operator \
  deployment/tigera-operator
Level 4: Check the CNI files on the node
sudo ls -lah /etc/cni/net.d/
sudo ls -lah /opt/cni/bin/

sudo cat /etc/cni/net.d/*calico*

Verify that the configuration exists and the referenced binaries are installed.

Level 5: Check container runtime and kubelet logs
sudo journalctl -u kubelet --since "30 minutes ago"

sudo journalctl -u containerd --since "30 minutes ago"

Filter:

sudo journalctl -u kubelet | grep -Ei "cni|network|sandbox|calico"
Level 6: Check pod IP allocation
kubectl get pods -A -o wide

kubectl get ippools.projectcalico.org -o yaml

calicoctl ipam show
calicoctl ipam show --show-blocks

Check for:

Exhausted IP pools
Pool selector not matching the node
Pod CIDR overlap
Node using an incorrect IP address
Disabled pool
Block affinity problems
Level 7: Check routing

On the source node:

ip route
ip rule
ip neigh

For Calico interfaces:

ip link show | grep cali
ip route | grep cali

For BGP mode:

calicoctl node status

Check whether peers show:

Established

A BGP session that is Idle, Active or repeatedly reconnecting usually indicates addressing, firewall, ASN or peering configuration problems.

Level 8: Check policy
kubectl get networkpolicy -A
kubectl get globalnetworkpolicies.projectcalico.org

Check the pod labels:

kubectl get pod <pod> -n <namespace> --show-labels

A policy may be valid but select the wrong pod because of an incorrect label.

Level 9: Capture packets

Find the source and destination pods:

kubectl get pods -A -o wide

Capture on the node:

sudo tcpdump -ni any host <pod-ip>

Capture a particular port:

sudo tcpdump -ni any \
  host <pod-ip> and port 8080

Useful interpretation:

No packets leave source pod:
    Pod, application, policy or local interface problem

Packets leave source but not source node:
    Source-node route or policy problem

Packets reach destination node but not destination pod:
    Destination route, veth or policy problem

Request reaches destination but response does not return:
    Reverse route, policy, NAT or asymmetric-routing problem
10. Debugging inside a pod’s network namespace

Get the pod sandbox:

sudo crictl pods
sudo crictl inspectp <sandbox-id>

Find its PID and enter the network namespace:

sudo nsenter -t <pid> -n ip addr
sudo nsenter -t <pid> -n ip route
sudo nsenter -t <pid> -n ss -lntup

This lets you inspect the exact interfaces, routes and sockets visible to the pod.

11. Calico data planes
iptables

The traditional Calico Linux data plane. Felix programs Linux routes and iptables rules, while kube-proxy commonly handles Kubernetes Service forwarding.

Debug with:

sudo iptables-save | grep cali
sudo iptables -L -n -v
sudo iptables -t nat -L -n -v
nftables

Calico supports an nftables data plane. It must be paired with kube-proxy in nftables mode, and Calico’s current documentation lists modern Linux kernel and nft requirements.

Debug with:

sudo nft list ruleset
eBPF

Calico eBPF can replace kube-proxy’s Service handling and implement networking and policy using programs attached to Linux kernel hooks. Its goals include lower latency, higher throughput and better source-IP preservation.

Debug with:

sudo bpftool prog show
sudo bpftool map show
sudo tc filter show dev <interface> ingress
sudo tc filter show dev <interface> egress

Do not enable eBPF merely because it sounds newer. First confirm kernel support, cloud compatibility and how kube-proxy is currently managed.

12. Five concepts to remember
1. CNI is a specification; Calico is an implementation.

2. CNI creates pod connectivity.
   NetworkPolicy controls which connectivity is allowed.

3. Calico CNI creates interfaces.
   Calico IPAM assigns addresses.
   Felix programs routes and security rules.

4. VXLAN/IPIP hide pod packets inside node packets.
   BGP advertises real routes without necessarily encapsulating them.

5. Troubleshoot in this order:
   Pod → CNI → IPAM → interface → route → policy → packet capture.

A strong practical learning sequence is:

CNI lifecycle
    ↓
Linux namespaces and veth
    ↓
Pod IPAM
    ↓
Same-node pod traffic
    ↓
Cross-node pod traffic
    ↓
Kubernetes Services
    ↓
NetworkPolicy
    ↓
Calico GlobalNetworkPolicy
    ↓
BGP/VXLAN
    ↓
tcpdump-based troubleshooting
